Happy Geek Desk owner here. If anyone&#039;s put off on the price, you can (hopefully still) order just the full mechanical base and put your own wood top on it. It&#039;s a $220 savings easily. And you can just use plywood (reinforce it if you like. It&#039;s worked fine, my top flexes but only when I lean on it. I recommend doing up the surface right with stain, poly, to make it finished for you. I used oak ply.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I think with the standing desk, you need the pads that the barbers and checkout clerks often have. A cushy pad will help your feet. I don&#039;t have one, but I want one. soft slippers would work too.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I probably switch my desk position three times every long work session and for shorter evening sessions (mine is at home) I usually keep it raised. Unintended benefit is the kid can&#039;t reach get to the computer stuff or my papers on my desk too.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The motor is kinda loud but it appears to be a good mechanism. It&#039;s a pretty straight forward assembly but I think I would set aside a bit of time to be careful and get help if you&#039;re not inclined.

I&#039;ve been standing for about a month at home. I mostly work at home, although 2-3 days a week I work at a client site where there&#039;s no alternative to sitting in a chair.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The leg and back muscle soreness is gone now. But like you, I&#039;ve some discomfort in my feet, however it has decreased substantially in the last week or two. I deal with this discomfort by occasionally grabbing my netbook and relocating to a chair and footstool where I prop up my feet to give them a rest.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
At first it felt strange to stand. For the first week I thought of giving it up, but that quickly went away as I realized that sitting was just a habit to overcome. Now I can&#039;t imagine going back.
